F1_variation_markdown2.0

Stephen Bovio

3/24/2021

Aim

This project uses Admixem to simulate F1 hybrids under various genetic architectures and selection parameters and compares the coefficient of variation to that of the parental species. See: https://github.com/melop/admixem for instructions on installing and running Admixem. Next, a decision tree (https://www.guru99.com/r-decision-trees.html) is used to predict which genetic architectures and selection parameters are more likely to cause F1 hybrids to have a smaller coefficient of variaton than the parental species.

Genertic architecture

Genome Size: 1 GB, 10 100Mb chromosomes

Recombination: Recombination hotspots are evenly distributed along each chromosome

Number of genes contributing to trait of interest: 10

Parameters Simulated

I simulated all combinations of the following variables for a total of 1584 unique parameter combinations (ie 2 linkage states * 11 gene actions * 6 initial allele frequencies * 2 effect sizes * 6 selection parameters)

linkage gene action initial allele frequency pop1 pop2 effect size selection
unlinked additive 1.0 / 0.0 0.1 no selection
linked dominant 0.9 / 0.1 0.9/0.01 frequency-dependent (NS)
additive + dominant 0.8 / 0.2 negative frequency-dependent (NS)
epi1aa + additive 0.7 / 0.3 directional selection (NS)
epi1ad + additive 0.6 / 0.4 frequency-dependent (SS)
epi1da + additive 0.5 / 0.5 directional selection (SS)
epi1dd + additive
epi5aa
epi5ad
epi5da
epi5dd

Linkage

I simulated two linkage states: unlinked and linked

Gene Action and Effect Sizes

For each gene action, I simulated two different effect sizes. One where all ten loci had the same effect size (0.1), and another where one locus or epistatic pair contributed ~90% of the variation, while ~10% of the variation was distributed evenly among the remaining loci.

Selection

The formualas below will yield a value between 0 and 1 that determine the probability of mating (for SS) or surivival (for NS).

selection formula
no selection none
frequency-dependent (NS) exp( - pow( Couter_Trait PopCourter_Avg_Trait , 2)/(2 * pow(PopCourter_Std_Trait/2,2)))
negative frequency-dependent (NS) 1 - exp( - pow( Couter_Trait PopCourter_Avg_Trait , 2)/(2 * pow(PopCouter_Std_Trait/2,2)))
directional selection (NS) exp( - pow( Courter_Trait - (PopCourter_Avg_Trait-PopCourter_Std_Trait) , 2)/(2 * pow(PopCourter_Std_Trait/2,2)))
frequency-dependent (SS) exp( - pow( Couter_Trait PopCourter_Avg_Trait , 2)/(2 * pow(PopCourter_Std_Trait/2,2)))
directional selection (SS) exp( - pow( Courter_Trait - (PopCourter_Avg_Trait-PopCourter_Std_Trait) , 2)/(2 * pow(PopCourter_Std_Trait/2,2)))

Admixem

The bash script below simulates 100 replicates at various initial allele frequencies (see parameters_simulated table for all initial allele frequencies) for a given set of parameters. In this case, one in which the phenotype of interest is determined by 10 additive unlinked loci, distributed among 10 indepedent chromosomes, each with an effect size of 0.1 and no natural or sexual selection. After 100 replicates at a given initial allele frequency, the mean and coefficient of variation are plotted and whether the 95% confidence interval of the mean hybrid phenotype overlaps with either of the parentals is determined. In addition, the proportion of replicates where the overlap between hybrid and parental populations is calculated. Ive only included this particular set of parameter conditions, but all comibinations from the parameters_simulated table were simulated. Briefly, the simulation establishes 50 males in parental pop1 and 50 females in parental pop2. Next, 25 males and females from pop1 and 2 migrate into a breeding deme. Here, females evaluate all males in the population and mate.

Bash Script

The following bash script depends on several R scripts and admixem configuration files which can be found below as well. See: https://github.com/melop/admixem for instructions on configuring these files.

#load packages
library(ggplot2, lib.loc = "/scratch/user/rbovio/R_LIBS_USER/3.6.2-intel-2019b-recommended-mt")
library(reshape2, lib.loc = "/scratch/user/rbovio/R_LIBS_USER/3.6.2-intel-2019b-recommended-mt")

#store command line arguements as variables
arrArgs <- commandArgs(trailingOnly = TRUE)
parameters<-as.character(arrArgs[1])
p1_af<-as.character(arrArgs[2])
p2_af<-as.character(arrArgs[3])

parameters_list = strsplit(parameters,"_")
linkage<- parameters_list[[1]][1]
gene_action = parameters_list[[1]][2]
esize<- parameters_list[[1]][3]
ss<- parameters_list[[1]][4]
ns<- parameters_list[[1]][5]


#create a dataframe to store the mean/sd/cv phenotype for each iteration/replicate
df = data.frame(NULL)

#create parameter counters
proportion_overlap_mean_p1 = 0
proportion_overlap_mean_p2 = 0
novelty = 0 #95% CI doesn't overlap with p1 or p2
num_failed_sims = 0

#loop through each directory (ie iteration)
for(i in 1:100){
  setwd(paste0("/scratch/user/rbovio/admixem3.0/admixem-master3.0/bin/F1_",parameters,"_",i))
  f = 'hybrids00'
  if(file.exists(f)==FALSE){
    num_failed_sims = num_failed_sims + 1
    next
  }
  #get parental and hybrid phenotype values
  p1m_data = read.delim(file = "parents00", header = TRUE)
  p2f_data = read.delim(file = "parents01", header = TRUE)
  hm_data = read.delim(file = "hybrids00", header = TRUE)
  hf_data = read.delim(file = "hybrids01", header = TRUE)
  
  
  #append to the dataframe
  df = rbind(df, c(i,
                   mean(p1m_data$Trait1),
                   mean(p2f_data$Trait1),
                   mean(c(hm_data$Trait1,hf_data$Trait1)), # EDIT HERE mean(ns$x)
                   sd(p1m_data$Trait1),
                   sd(p2f_data$Trait1),
                   sd(c(hm_data$Trait1,hf_data$Trait1)),
                   sd(p1m_data$Trait1)/mean(p1m_data$Trait1),
                   sd(p2f_data$Trait1)/mean(p2f_data$Trait1),
                   sd(c(hm_data$Trait1,hf_data$Trait1))/mean(c(hm_data$Trait1,hf_data$Trait1))))
  
  # Summary statistics for each replicate in order to determine proportion of replicates that show novel phenotypes
  p1_mean = mean(p1m_data$Trait1)
  p1_sd = sd(p1m_data$Trait1)
  p1_cv = p1_sd/p1_mean
  p1_n = nrow(p1m_data)
  p1_error <- qnorm(0.975)*p1_sd/sqrt(p1_n)
  p1_left  <- p1_mean - p1_error
  p1_right <- p1_mean + p1_error
  p1_sum_stat <- cbind(p1_left, p1_mean, p1_right)
  
  p2_mean = mean(p2f_data$Trait1)
  p2_sd = sd(p2f_data$Trait1)
  p2_cv = p2_sd/p2_mean
  p2_n = nrow(p2f_data)
  p2_error <- qnorm(0.975)*p2_sd/sqrt(p2_n)
  p2_left  <- p2_mean - p2_error
  p2_right <- p2_mean + p2_error
  p2_sum_stat <- cbind(p2_left, p2_mean, p2_right)
  
  h_mean = mean(c(hm_data$Trait1,hf_data$Trait1))
  h_sd = sd(c(hm_data$Trait1,hf_data$Trait1))
  h_cv = h_sd/h_mean
  h_n = nrow(hm_data)+nrow(hf_data)
  h_error <- qnorm(0.975)*h_sd/sqrt(h_n)
  h_left  <- h_mean - h_error
  h_right <- h_mean + h_error
  h_sum_stat <- cbind(h_left, h_mean, h_right)
  
  #check range overlap
  p1_range = c(p1_sum_stat[1,1],p1_sum_stat[1,3])
  p2_range = c(p2_sum_stat[1,1],p2_sum_stat[1,3])
  h_range = c(h_sum_stat[1,1],h_sum_stat[1,3])
  if(p1_range %overlaps% h_range == TRUE){
    proportion_overlap_mean_p1 = proportion_overlap_mean_p1 + 1
    # print(p1_range)
    # print(h_range)
  }
  if(p2_range %overlaps% h_range == TRUE){
    proportion_overlap_mean_p2 = proportion_overlap_mean_p2 + 1
    # print(p2_range)
    # print(h_range)
  }
  if(p1_range %overlaps% h_range == FALSE & p2_range %overlaps% h_range == FALSE){
    novelty = novelty + 1
  }
  colnames(df) = c("replicate", 
                   "p1_mean","p2_mean","h_mean",
                   "p1_sd","p2_sd","h_sd",
                   "p1_cv","p2_cv","h_cv")  
     
  setwd("/scratch/user/rbovio/admixem3.0/admixem-master3.0/bin")
}

df$gene_action =  gene_action
df$p1_af = p1_af
df$p2_af = p2_af
df$esize = esize

write.csv(df, paste0("df_",parameters,".csv"), quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE)

Decision Tree

When we do this for every parameter combination, we can use a decision tree to create a model that predicts the value of a target variable (ie cvstatus) based on several input variables (ie linkage, gene action, allele frequency, effect sizes, and selection).

  • Each node shows
    • the predicted class (larger or smaller),
    • the predicted probability of having a smaller coefficient of variation,
    • the percentage of observations in the node.
Below is the Rscript used to construct the decision tree.

CLICK HERE TO SEE RSCRIPT

Accuracy for test: 0.895580110497238

  • Key findings:

    • When the natural selection parameter is not equal to nons,nsnfd,nsds (ie ns = nsfd) AND p1_af < 0.95 AND p2_af > 0.15 than there is a 96% probability that the hybrid CV will be smaller. 12% of the simulations fall under this parameter space.

    • 27% of simulations yield hybrid CVs that are smaller than either parental population. Of these, gene action is only relevant for 17% of simulations

    • Sexual selection doesnt appear to predict CV status
